courses.learning_outcomes:
By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. design units of work, lessons, teaching/learning resources, and assessment items that are in line with the current methodology of second language teaching and the official English Language curriculum in Hong Kong;
2. apply a range of English Language Teaching techniques in the classroom;
3. critique and evaluate English lessons taught in the secondary school;
4. demonstrate a disposition towards continuing professional learning and developing their personal theory of language teaching

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to:
• be familiar with the NSS\_Economics syllabus and DSE;
• apply a variety of instructional strategies in lessons;
• design, apply, evaluate and modify teaching resources;
• design & apply different assessment modes to evaluate students’ learning outcomes, and
• do reflective self-evaluation to improve students’ learning.

1. Develop awareness for life-long professional growth of a mathematics teacher.

2. Understand the content and rationale behind Hong Kong secondary school mathematics curriculum;
3. Construct lesson plans by selecting and sequencing “big ideas” to teach secondary school mathematics;
4. Recognize different strategies, methods and techniques for teaching mathematics;
5. Use appropriate teaching resources such as physical teaching aids and computer software to teach mathematics concepts and procedures;
6. Determine prerequisite knowledge, common difficulties and effective teaching strategies for learning different mathematics topics;
7. Construct tests and other diagnosis to evaluate the effectiveness of mathematics learning and teaching;
8. Design mathematics related activities to enrich mathematics learning and teaching

At the end of the course, course participants should be able to:

* apply their understanding of the design principles of the Citizenship and Social Development curriculum in unit and lesson planning;
* develop learning and teaching strategies based on the constructivist view of learning;
* design learning and teaching activities that engage pupils in enquiry learning;
* design assessment activities that align with the aims and objectives of Citizenship and Social Development.

