courses.course_syllabus:
• The definitions of curriculum;
• Relationships between curriculum, instruction and assessment;
• The commonplaces of curriculum design;
• Curriculum aims and objectives;
• Selection and organization of learning experiences;
• Student assessment and curriculum evaluation;
• Models of curriculum design.

courses.learning_outcomes:
At the end of the course, students are expected to be able:

1. To identify the basic theories / concepts of curriculum evaluation and assessment;
2. To design appropriate assessment using the concepts as learnt in the module;
3. To critically analyze current issues related to curriculum evaluation and assessment in the context of Hong Kong and elsewhere.

Upon completing the course, students are expected to:

(1) Identify the key features of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations;
(2) State the merits and demerits of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations;
(3) Apply the basic principles of various teaching models and pedagogical orientations to real-life instructional design;
(4) Reflect critically on the current practice in schools and explore the possibilities of improving classroom teaching.

At the end of the course, participants will:

1. understand various pedagogical and technological conceptions related to ICT in education;
2. gain practical knowledge and skills in developing multimedia and online resources for educational use;
3. integrate multimedia and eLearning elements into the process of teaching and learning;
4. design and implement ICT-enhanced inquiry-based learning in their subjects of teaching.

At the end of the course, participants are expected to be able to:

1. recognise and articulate the essence and role of STEM education in the 21st century;
2. identify various pedagogical and curriculum approaches to STEM education;
3. design STEM lessons and materials to meet student needs in secondary education;
4. develop and implement authentic assessments for STEM activities;
5. implement STEM oriented activities in both formal and informal curriculum.

1. understand basic structures and processes of schooling in local and global context and enhance their roles as effective teachers in their workplace;
2. develop their understanding in the theory and practice of schools and functions of schools from various perspectives;
3. extend knowledge on educational policy and practice in Hong Kong by applying theoretical ideas from research;
4. learn to identify and critique education policies.

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to be able to :

1. recognize the HK education system and the key contents of some educational policies nowadays ;
2. understand the implementation of the educational policies in schools;
3. apply the relevant concepts to analyze the implications of the educational policies.

After completion of this course (20 hrs.), students are expected to:

(1) develop a critical understanding of the place of values in moral education and the meaning of morality in education;
(2) reflect on their being moral teachers in relation to aims of educational practice and their professional identity;
(3) be able to develop moral pedagogies possibly in the form of case studies or lesson plans.

1. Understand the development of the teaching profession in Hong Kong;
2. Comprehend different types of professional development programmes for teachers in Hong Kong;
3. Understand various influential factors on teacher development;
4. Reflect on and improve individual practices by integrating oneself with their school settings

1. Identify at-risk students and their main characteristics in the classroom;
2. Explain the various causes contributing to disadvantaged students from psychological, sociological and neurological perspectives;
3. Understand the concepts of protective factors and resilience in working with at-risk students;
4. Describe the CBUPO approach of working with disadvantaged students;
5. Exercise judgment in the planning and design of classroom processes and curriculum for disadvantaged students;
6. Express personal values and visions for the education of disadvantaged students.

At the end of this course, students should be able to:

1. recognize the key features of education in different periods in HK ;
2. explain the relations between the social development and the educational changes in HK ;
3. reflect upon the functions of education in the contexts of Hong Kong society.

After the course, students will be able to:
(1) acquire understanding of parents’ role in children education with diversified needs;
(2) develop awareness of ways to enhance home school communication for meeting students with diversified needs;
(3) improve parental involvement in school activities in supporting the learning needs of students with mixed abilities in inclusive environments;
(4) build trust and connected relationship with parents in their community in dealing with learners with diversified needs; and
(5) construct a comprehensive model of home school collaboration according to students’ needs in the school context.

By the end of the course, students will be able to:

1. demonstrate competence and broad understanding of the professional standards and basic legal knowledge for teachers in Hong Kong;
2. identify moral dilemmas facing teachers and make responsible decisions by considering different ethical perspectives, and finding the best possible way forward for all stakeholders;
3. act conscientiously with regard to the professional standards and the law, and collaborate ethically and competently in multi-disciplinary and multi-cultural teams; and
4. develop a commitment to the teaching profession and reflect on the professional standards in individual practices.

Upon completion of this course, students are expected to:

(1) achieve a comprehensive and critical understanding of various perspectives on meaning related issues in life;

(2) develop attitudes and skills to deal with life and well-being issues located in their quest for meaning of life;

(3) apply what has been learned to deal with important life issues (e.g. life, death and different dimensions of well-being) with a view to enhancing their intrapersonal, interpersonal and transcendence competencies.

By the end of the course, students are expected to be able to:

- Describe the major theories and empirical findings in the field of adolescent development;
- Describe the methods used by researchers to examine adolescent development;
- Discuss the reciprocal influences between adolescents’ development and their social contexts;
- Better understand adolescents’ perspectives, experience, and psychological needs, thereby become more equipped to support their development.

After taking the course, students are expected to

1. understand the basic concepts, principles, and issues about educational assessment and evaluation;
2. understand the properties of different assessment techniques for assessing students’ learning, such as objective test items, constructive-response test items, performances assessment and etc.;
3. apply the techniques to construct and appraise objective-type and constructive-type test items; and

4. evaluate and revise a classroom test by applying assessment/measurement concepts and the practical guidelines of constructing achievement tests.

At the conclusion of the course, participants will be able to:
1. develop an understanding of the important factors affecting classroom management and discipline;
2. adopt several key preventive measures to establish a positive learning environment;
3. acquire some intervention strategies in solving discipline problems;
4. explore and develop a personal approach to classroom management and discipline

The intended Learning Outcomes of TP are that students will:
(1) demonstrate teaching competence ;
(2) integrate and apply pedagogical content knowledge in practice;
(3) apply concepts of reflective practice to authentic classroom and
(4) develop appropriate attitudes and values of a qualified teacher.
